Club of Negative Interest Rates
Brussels – For much of the last decade, central banks have made only limited progress in containing powerful global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has kept interest rates at zero and has also undertaken multiple unprecedented expansions of its balance sheet through large-scale bond purchases.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have all followed in the Federal Reserve’s footsteps, implementing their own versions of what is known as “quantitative easing” (QE).
But inflation has not reasonably risen anywhere.
Despite these countries all battling deflationary pressures, their monetary policies – and economic performance – are diverging.
The growth in the United States and the United Kingdom is now strong enough to allow them to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the eurozone and Japan are increasing their QE programs and pushing policy long-term interest rates further into negative territory.
What is the reason for this distinction?
The brief answer is debt.
For decades, the United States and the United Kingdom have had current account deficits and thus been debtors, while the eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses and thus been creditors.
Negative interest rates benefit debtor nations at the expense of creditor nations, so the global economic crisis-era negative interest rates stimulated recovery in the United States and the United Kingdom but had little effect on the Eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
So far, negative interest rates prevail in most creditor countries around the world – such as Denmark and Switzerland, which have sustained large current-account surpluses – not only for long-term government bonds and other “risk-free” debts but also for medium-term bonds.
This is not good at all.
Despite low interest rates being ineffective, these economies' central banks still adhere to this policy.
If you suggest that QE or lowering interest rates cannot benefit the economy, they will change the subject and反驳 the notion that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — on the surface, this seems unassailable.
But in reality, it is riddled with flaws.
The basic economics course mentions the peculiar phenomenon of a "backward-bending savings supply curve": in certain environments, lowering interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
Because lower interest rates reduce savers' income, they will decrease spending, especially if they are saving for retirement.
None of this is meant to deny the general rule - which forms the basis of modern monetary decision-making - that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other expenditures.
Only the impact differs due to the different debt conditions of economies.
In a closed economy, each creditor has a debtor, so whatever the creditor loses due to very low interest rates, the debtor should benefit.
But in an economy with large net foreign asset positions, creditors are naturally many more than debtors.
For a country with a significant amount of foreign debt, the situation is exactly the opposite.
Therefore, the effects of monetary policy with interest rate lower bounds differ between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important because foreign asset positions were typically small (in terms of the percentage of GDP).
However, today, the positions in foreign assets of the major industrialized economies are large and becoming more diversified, partly because of the leveraging that contributed to the global financial crisis of 2007–2008.
In fact, at the national level, leverage is still increasing.
Despite overall improvements in current account imbalances since the start of the financial crisis, they have not reversed.
This means that surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, creating a divide with deficit economies.
Some commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, have substantial current-account surpluses when oil prices are high, making them notable exceptions to the divergence in foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, world oil prices have experienced a dramatic plunge, reversing the wealth trends of these countries.
Their export revenues have plummeted dramatically—many countries have seen them fall by half—and have forced them into deficits, relying on vast sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the commodity boom.
Now, a significant reduction in spending is inevitable.
Industrialized economies face entirely different challenges.
Their problem – to some extent, a luxury problem – is ensuring that consumers spend the windfall from import price reductions.
But in creditor countries, negative interest rates do not seem to be advancing this goal; indeed, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This differentiation also exists within the eurozone.
Despite the eurozone as a whole being a creditor economy, it includes debtor countries.
Debt-laden economies like Spain and Portugal now often run current account surpluses and are reducing their debt.
But the current-account surpluses of traditional debtor countries are too high, leading to an ongoing asymmetry between debtor and creditor countries.
The most noteworthy development is that Germany’s current-account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP since the financial crisis began, meaning that the surpluses accumulated during this period alone exceed the totals of previous years.
Following the current trend, Germany's foreign creditor position could increase from 60% of GDP to 100%.
The central bank governor should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend toward central bank independence because central bank governors tend to be less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bankers seem to have little patience for low inflation, despite the gradual filling of output gaps, and with full employment achieved in both the US and Japan.
Central bank governors of debtor countries must stop using monetary easing that could be detrimental to production to manipulate their economies.
Conversely, they should allow the recovery to develop at its own pace, even if it is slow, and wait for the base effects of oil prices dropping to fade out.
The ECB president, Mario Draghi, recently acknowledged that under today's global circumstances, the current monetary policy approach might not be effective.
But promising more is not the solution.
